0 stars if I can give that. Absolutely disappointed with this restaurant and my entire order. I ordered Chicken Tikka Masala and Chicken Vindaloo on DoorDash which came super quick. And with anticipation and hunger, I was expecting some really tasty food. But to my horror, both dishes were just plain oily and tasteless. Like you cannot even taste the spices that both dishes are supposed to have. They are both oddly watery and oily at the same time. The Vindaloo only has four pieces of potato and chicken scraps. But the worst is definitely the Chicken Tikka Masala. How can they get that one wrong? It’s such a classic. Instead of the nice typical orange and creamy texture, the chicken tikka masala from Madina is flaming red so obvious it’s from food coloring because the chicken pieces are also stained red, and water/oily in texture. Also the nan is super thick, might as well call it a pancake. See pictures for what I mean about the nasty texture. I even had to scoop out the oils before eating it. Both myself and my niece did not enjoy this food - what a waste of my money and such a big disappointment. I’m so upset that I had to write this review and this is my first Google review.  Will not ever repurchase.

2 best friends, an Indian & a Pakistani, create a casual cafe with food from both nation's. It's no-frills. You order what you want from the counter,  a glass covered display of hot plates and appetizers, tell them you're having it in,  then take a table.  The waiter will bring you a set-up and a pitcher of iced water,  and then the dishes begin to arrive. The menu is available at their website as a PDF,  and explains the foods,  so you can decide in your order ahead.  Or just point to things and ask the counter guy "What's that? Prices are reasonable,  but the A/C was barely adequate .

I called back again to make the delivery order and attempted to pay with a credit card, as I always have, and was told I had to pay in cash. Inexpensive, comfortable, and friendly, Madina would be a neat place worth occasionally visiting were the food better. Nothing I had was bad, it was just completely generic and dull. It wasn't spicy, the portions (apart from the rice) were smallish, and neither the recipes nor the ingredients were noteworthy. In another part of the country, I'd just be sad that Indian food gets such a lukewarm ambassador, but in the neighbourhood Madina's in, there are excellent (and equally inexpensive) alternatives within a few blocks.  The service was excellent though, and when I was done eating I was impressed that they immediately knew what I owed and got me change faster than anywhere else I've ever eaten.
